on2star  aIn this volume, specialists from traditionally separate areas in economics and finance investigate issues at the conjunction of their fields. They argue that financial decisions of the firm can affect real economic activity-and this is true for enough firms and consumers to have significant aggregate economic effects. They demonstrate that important differences-asymmetries-in access to information between "borrowers" and "lenders" ("insiders" and "outsiders") in financial transactions affect investment decisions of firms and the organization of financial markets. The original research emphasizes the role of information problems in explaining empirically important links between internal finance and investment, as well as their role in accounting for observed variations in mechanisms for corporate control.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCorporationsxCongressesxFinance. 0aCorporationsxFinancevCongresses. 0aInvestmentsxCongressesxMathematical models. 0aInvestmentsxMathematical modelsvCongresses. 0aSecuritiesvCongresses. 0aSecuritiesxCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aHubbard, R. Glenn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226355948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226355948.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles